72-year-old female brought from nursing facility with altered mental status and fever x 12 hours. Per facility records, she was in her usual state of health yesterday. Baseline is ambulatory with walker, oriented x3. History of recurrent UTIs, COPD, CHF (EF 35%), diabetes type 2. Medications include metformin, furosemide, lisinopril, and albuterol inhaler.

Vitals on arrival at 1100: BP 88/52, HR 118, temp 103.2, RR 24, SpO2 91% on RA. On exam, confused and oriented to name only, tachycardic, dry mucous membranes, suprapubic tenderness. GCS 13 (E3V4M6). qSOFA score 3 (AMS, RR ≥22, SBP ≤100).

Labs at 1115: WBC 22.4 with 15% bands, lactate 4.8, BMP shows creatinine 2.1 (baseline 1.0 per records), glucose 89. UA grossly positive — large leuk esterase, nitrites positive, too numerous to count bacteria and WBC. Blood cultures x2 drawn. Procalcitonin 8.4. Chest X-ray shows no acute infiltrate. BNP 890.

Hour-1 sepsis bundle initiated: 30ml/kg NS bolus started at 1110, blood cultures drawn before antibiotics. Ceftriaxone 2g IV and metronidazole 500mg IV started at 1120. Repeat lactate at 1300 shows 3.2 (improving from 4.8). Repeat BP after fluids 96/60 — borderline. Norepinephrine drip started at 1315 at 5mcg/min, titrated to MAP >65.

Discussed with Dr. Robinson, hospitalist, at 1330 — she recommends ICU admission given vasopressor requirement and AMS. Agrees with antibiotic coverage.

Discussed with Dr. Kim, infectious disease, at 1345 — recommends broadening to piperacillin-tazobactam given healthcare-associated UTI source and recent facility residence. Recommends urine culture sensitivity-guided de-escalation in 48-72 hours. Changed antibiotics per ID recommendation at 1400.

Disposition: admit to ICU, critical care team notified.
